review_blob:
Pours golden thick and viscous. Strong herbaceous hop and citrus aroma you can smell across the room. Really enjoyable

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: Amager / Surly Todd - The Axe Man

review_blob: Best of 6 in the IPA flight at yard house, las vegas. Medium amber in color, slightly foggy.
Medium amber in color. #5 in a flight at yard house. Malty resinous in the mouth. Aroma of malt. Pretty typical dipa.
beer_name: Uinta Detour Double India Pale Ale

review_blob: Darkest in color of the flight - citrus aroma and citrus flavor. Frontrunner on the flight for me with 4 tasted and 2 to go.
Palest IPA of the flight. Light floral aroma . Aside from the medium bitterness, not much flavor. Closed off
Medium amber color. Smell of banana and carmelized sugars. Taste of carmelized sugars and resin. Lots of tiny bubbles in the mouth. Crisp. Kind of a cross between an ipa and a belgian pale
Just a monster - dark pour, onslaught of coffee and dark chocolate, burnt caramel. assertive, but smooth.

Is it the best pumpkin ale Ive had? No. But its not the worst. And at $6 a six pack its a darn good value. Golden pour, white head. Aroma is pumpkin spice and a bit of wheat, perhaps. Think "Blue Moon" but pumpkin instead of corriander seed. Nothing too complicated, but exactly what I was after today.
I was disappointed in this one. Bottled. Kind of a sour note with a nutty malt finish. Had to search hard for any kind of vanilla note. bad bottle?

Drank from the bottle. Interesting character to it. Not much of a head, but a surprising amount of co2 on the tongue, given that. sweet hops and caramel malt and just a slight note of the whiskey barrels. enjoyable and above average.
beer_name: Rogue John John Dead Guy Ale

review_blob:
A wheat bear on the order of something like Blue Moon; except, replace the corriander with watermelon. At first, it is a bit confusing, as the watermelon isnt really noticeable until the finish. But Im finding that a cold one of these suits me perfectly on these hot 90 degree days. Something about the refreshingness of a wheat beer and the sweetness of watermelon. Definitely recommend when youre looking for something simple, light, and refreshing. (And if you like watermelon.)

Body - light-medium, with a carbonation level on bar with a basic sparkling water...crisp and refreshing
Finish - medium and very definitely watermelon. But balanced with the blue-moon-like wheat flavor
Armona - not much to write home about
Appearance - Drank from a can
beer_name: 21st Amendment Hell or High Watermelon Wheat

review_blob: Rust colored pour with thin to no head. Obvious raspberry nose with hints of malt. In the mouth, crisp, with raspberry and a sweet maltiness. Pretty much like a rasberry desert in beer form. Gotta be in the right mood for this one.
Citrusy hop nose. Caramel, honey. grass, Roast and resin in the mouth Delicious, but no Hopslam.
650ml, 2010. On the nose, fresh-baked bread, chocolate, coffee, caramel, and of course Bourbon and oak. Dark.  Strong bourbon/coffee in the mouth. Truly delicious.
I had this about a year ago at Bulldog  in St Paul. I remember it being quite hoppy and a bit out of balance.
beer_name: Avery The Maharaja Imperial India Pale Ale

review_blob: Pours orange with nice pale head and good lacing. More citrus-y than I expected. The hops are there, but not as pronounced as in most American style DIPAs. I think I may actually prefer the 60 minute.

This is a real beast. Pours very dark, almost ebony. Aroma of coffee, the darkest of chocolates, and bourbon. Even the head is dark. In the mouth the flavor is strong--itll knock you over strong. This is a beer to savor. A bit too strong on the coffee flavors for my preference, but still delicious. If you like coffee and you like bourbon, do everything you can to taste this beer.

2010 bottling. A definite pumpkin ale. Strong on the pumpkin / pumpkin pie flavor. Less cinnamon/nutmeg than some other pumpkin ales. Somewhat bready. On the whole, the flavors felt muted. Much better than the Shipyard pumpkin ale. More pumpkiny than the New Holland Ichabod, but I have to give the higher ranking to the Ichabod as a matter of personal taste and preference for more spice. If memory serves, flavor is more-muted than with the Buffalo Bills as well... I will need to re-taste that one and then update this note.

So, as a bit of a disclaimer, I love my pumpkin ales. Which is strange, considering I dont really like pumpkin. Perhaps that explains my enjoyment of this particular pumpkin ale. It is a bit lighter on the pumpkin flavor than some others, with the palate dominated by spices such as cinnamon and nutmeg.

Pours dark. Nose of coffee, dark chocolate, and milk chocolate.  A whiff of alcohol.  Possibly a hint of red fruit and caramel.  Initially, in the mouth, a real bruiser. all 100 IBU are showing here. As the beer had a chance to breathe, the balance started to develop. The alcohol that had dominated the first taste is much more tame after 5 minutes.  A chocolate-covered cherry finish that goes on for some time, but not sweet -- perfectly balanced by the bitterness. A bit of a pine/resin note too. Very impressive.

Pours dark gold/copper with light head. Aroma is distinctly "beer"... leines-like. Fine bubble carbonation.  Bitter on the finish, but not much in terms of character. Id almost be inclined to place this as a cross between a good IPA and a macrobrew lager.  Its ok, but skippable.

Dark brown, almost black with a real thin chocolate-milk colored head. On the nose, a blend of blueberry and coffee, chocolate. It smells lovely, kind of like blueberry oatmeal. The taste is... interesting.  Id best-describe it as a stout with a coffee-finish, that also has a note of chocolate-covered blueberry to it. The initial mouthfeel is a bit dissonant, but it settles into a smooth finish. An intriguing change of pace.

Dark... near-black with little-to-no head. Seriously. Aroma dark fruit...cherry, oak. In the mouth, much less heavy than expected. Smoke, oak, whiskey, sunflower seed, and slight notes of dark fruit, cocoa, and coffee. Really quite contemplative and enjoyable.
Dark opaque pour with a tin tan head. Aroma of coffee. Flavors of coffee and dark chocolate, a bit of cinnamon. A tasty oatmeal stout.
I remember this being a decent imperial stout, but nothing on the level of the Bells Expedition Stout. This one next to that is a bit harsher, more bitter and less complex.
beer_name: North Coast Old Rasputin Russian Imperial Stout

review_blob: A nice, hoppy beer. A reliable bottled beer. An orange/gold coloration in the glass. Personally I prefer this in the bottle to on tap...I just get a better bouquet from it. I made the mistake of having this after the Hopslam, however. Next to that, this paled. It is a solid IPA, however and Id recommend it.

Had this at Bulldog on tap. A delicious beer. Dark brown with a decent head. A solid quad; I like this better than the rochefort 10, but not as much as the westvleteren 12. Ill add notes if/when I find where I wrote them...

Pours a light caramel color but sits dark brown/opaque in the glass, settling into a small beige head with good lacing. 

The first thing to hit me from the aroma is spice... nutmeg, cinnamon, molasses, vanilla...then grains, a bit of a yeasty/bready note with subtle hits of raisin and cherry. Notes of leather.

In the mouth: bread, caramel, light cherry, finishing into darkchocolate/coffee, nuts. A perfect level of carbonation leaves the mouth warm and tingly. Not sweet, not bitter...excellent balance.

Finish goes on forever. The finish really sells this. It is seriously ridiculous, rivaling my favorite 99pt Sauternes.

Savor this.

Nice consistent murky dark brown pour with a thick, dense offwhite head. Served at about 50F. malt, burnt sugar, spice, bready, a little bit of metallic and fruit notes. Extraordinary balance with well-integrated flavors. Finish goes on and on.

As it opens up: cherry, a bit of cinnamon/raisin bread. Just delicious.
Murkey golden color, dense head with nice lacing. Lemon/citrus, nutmeg, ginger, wheat and a bitof something I cant place. Smooth hops. Delicious.

Black, with virtually no head. Smell of coffee and dark chocolate, maybe some dark cherry. The taste is bitter. Like biting into a coffee bean covered with unsweetened cooking chocolate, and something like a peanutty finish.
beer_name: Southern Tier Jah-va Imperial Coffee Stout

review_blob: Dark Amber/Copper in coloring with a dense, thick head on the pour. Coloring is even, a bit murky. In the mouth, something of a refreshing carbonation with caramelized sugar, maltiness, and hint of molasses and toffee. Possibly fig. Not as raisiny as the 10, which is a positive point, to me. Very well balanced.
Pale yellow, cloudy, white head. not terribly impressed by this one.  some citrus but the corriander wasnt detectable to me.
amber coloring, beige head. caramel, nuttiness, raisiny. didnt care for this one.

My new benchmark porter. Dark and tasty: coffee, dark chocolate, very rich but not overwhelming. More flavor and more bite than mainstream stouts. A great winter beer for when not feeling up to an Imperial Stout.

Medium amber pour. Nose is pine, hops, herbaceous/grassy, and a note of something sweeter, caramelized sugars perhaps. Flavor isnt much to speak of, but certainly on the bitter side. Finish settles into very nutty.. almond or peanut. Very contemplative.
beer_name: Moylans Hopsickle Imperial India Pale Ale

review_blob: Citrus, herbaceous, hoppy, everything youd want from an IPA and with good balance. Paler in color than the 120, somewhat cloudy-amber in coloring.

Certainly strong, but you wont notice it while drinking. Lots of carmelized fruity notes. Raisiny. Frankly a bit too raisiny for my taste, balanced toward the sweet side. 12oz bottle pours almost orange in color.  I would describe this as being to beer what Port is to wine.

Straw yellow in appearance with a massive head, more bubbly than champagne. The flavor is basc, lager-like, with a honey note. I detected neither the spiciness nor the fruitiness of the commercial deScription.
beer_name: Smuttynose Big Beer Series: Farmhouse Ale

review_blob: I tell you what: if you like tart cherries (think door county cherries) and you like stouts, you will like this. Serve it a hair warmer than you might usually. Flavor is the typical stout characteristics with a bit of tartness at the end. Serve too cold and the flavors clash, however. Personally, this is one I look forward to.
Very Dark in color. Strong notes of coffee and roast. A nice rich flavor. This is a strong beer, to be sure! Excellent one to turn to in the deep of winter.
Had this on tap at a place in Hartford, CT. I dont remember too much about it anymore other than that it was a so-so at best IPA with little of the character one hopes for when reaching for one.
This is pretty much exactly like Guinness Draught but with a bit more of what id describe as an iron note.

A mediocre pale ale. Bronze in color with a moderate head. Somewhat bitter but not in the good way. This will certainly do if Im looking IPA and its whats available, but this is about as basic as an IPA can be.
Had this on tap at a local Oktoberfest. Its a decent enough beer, I suppose, but there are certainly better options available. Golden/rust in color.
A nice, meaty stout. The foam rising to the top on the pour is something of a pretty sight. Notes of maltiness and coffee. This is my mainstay at the non-craftbeer bars.

A basic brown ale with a hint of iron on the aftertaste. Its not altogether pleasant on the first sip, but grows on you. One of the more quality mainstream brews, but not in the same league as the crafts.

A nice, smooth stout with a bit of a chocolate note. Be careful with the can-form: it will overflow very quickly if you open it warm or after having traveled with it. If you like Guinness, youll find this a treat.
Surprisingly smooth for an IPA...takes some getting used-to, but nice and contemplative once you do.
Love this beer. Hoppy but not as grassy as most IPA, but real bitter despite the fairly mediocre IBU. Dark copper in color.  Strong flavor that is too strong for some, but I love it.
beer_name: Flying Dog Double Dog Double Pale Ale
